choices.text:
my stuttering. You see, back in my country, I could speak just fine. It wasn’t until I came to America that I started developing a problem. People will probably tell you what their stuttering sounds like or where it happens, but for me, it comes anytime. There’s no pattern or rhyme. It’s there when I want it to be there, or I want it to be not there. For me, the stuttering is extremely personal, because it’s a part of me.

I cannot deny the fact that my stuttering is a part of my identity. While only I know how it feels and sounds, thousands of others know just what it is like, too. My stuttering means a lot to me, and to be told by someone that I’m okay or I’m doing well, would be a big slap in the face. Through the self-awareness and my interactions with others, I’ve learned to accept myself for who I am, because I simply cannot change myself for one person’s sake. Many of you wonder if I talk to myself. While that seems to be the general consensus, I get asked this question so often that I created a video explaining it: How People React When They Meet Me

I want to share this experience with others because they could benefit from it. Maybe someone out there is struggling with stuttering and doesn’t know where to turn to. I hope I can be that someone for them. I hope my story can mean something
